Title: PI STORY
Credit: Written by
Author: Upon Tyne — for Benjamin Cartwright
Source: Adapted from the author's Act I beat sheet
Draft date: June 2026
Notes: ACT I — working draft. Dark noir crime thriller. Parallel timelines · long takes · false climax.

====

FADE IN:

INT. NEIGHBORHOOD BAR — NIGHT

A narrow room that smells like bleach and old beer. One lamp lit. The stools are up on the tables except for two. Plastic sheeting hangs over the back booth, taped to the ceiling, catching the light like still water.

THE PI sits at the bar — fifties, gray coming in at the temples, a coat he hasn't taken off. He nurses the last inch of a whiskey. Across from him, THE BAR OWNER wipes a glass that's already clean.

THE BAR OWNER
Whatever happens in here tonight.

THE PI
It doesn't touch you.

THE BAR OWNER
That's not a promise a man like you should make easy.

THE PI
I don't make it easy.

The Bar Owner sets the glass down. Looks at the plastic sheeting like it's a thing he's agreed to and is already regretting.

THE BAR OWNER
Your partner. The one they put in the ground. He'd have walked out of here by now.

The PI doesn't look up.

THE PI
He's why I'm staying.

The Bar Owner takes his coat off the hook. Pauses at the side door.

THE BAR OWNER
Side door's open till two. After that you're on your own.

He leaves. The door clicks. The PI finishes the whiskey, sets the glass down soft, and stands.

He walks out the front.

CUT TO:

EXT. NEIGHBORHOOD STREET — CONTINUOUS

[[LONG TAKE — the camera finds the PI and does not let him go until noted. Gloria Jones, "Cry Baby," comes up under the opening credits.]]

The PI moves down the sidewalk with the quiet purpose of a man who has nowhere good to be and intends to get there anyway. Neon bleeds in the puddles. The city exhales around him — steam, a far-off siren, a kid's bike with no kid on it.

He doesn't hurry. He doesn't slow.

CUT TO:

INT. CORNER BODEGA — CONTINUOUS

A bell over the door. Fluorescent hum. The CLERK doesn't look up from his crossword. The PI goes to the counter and waits half a beat.

The Clerk slides a small package wrapped in brown paper across the counter, the way you'd pass salt.

The PI tucks it inside his coat, against his chest. Lays a folded bill on the counter. Leaves.

[[The package is the seed. Hold one extra frame on it before the coat closes.]]

CUT TO:

EXT. STREET CORNER — HOT DOG CART — CONTINUOUS

Credits end. The music drops to street sound.

The PI stops at a cart, more for the standing than the food. A YOUNG BEAT COP — eager, clean, too new to know what he's looking at — drifts over, recognizing a face from a briefing.

YOUNG BEAT COP
You're him. The broker. They said you used to carry a shield.

THE PI
They say a lot of things.

YOUNG BEAT COP
Is it true you can find out anything about anybody?

THE PI
(not unkind, just done)
Kid. Go find a corner that needs standing on.

The cop hesitates, then goes. The PI doesn't watch him leave. He's already looking down the street.

A DARK SEDAN turns the corner, slow.

CUT TO:

EXT. SIDE STREET — CONTINUOUS

The sedan eases to the curb. Tinted glass comes down two inches. THE CI — call him that; everyone does — leans into the gap, a man who has made a career of being slightly in shadow.

THE CI
You bring it?

The PI produces the brown-paper package. Doesn't hand it over yet.

THE PI
Names first.

THE CI
That's not how we —

THE PI
It's how it is tonight.

A long beat. The CI weighs it. Then he recites — flat, memorized, three names and a place. The PI takes none of it down. He doesn't need to.

THE CI (CONT'D)
And the one you really wanted. He'll be where you think he'll be. Same time. Same place.

The PI's jaw works once. He passes the package through the gap. The CI takes it, turns it over, satisfied.

THE CI (CONT'D)
You sure about tonight?

THE PI
No.

THE CI
Good answer.

The glass goes up. The sedan pulls away, taillights swallowed by the block. The PI watches it the length of the street — longer than he needs to.

[[The sedan and this man matter. Let the audience clock the car. It comes back.]]

The PI takes out his phone. Thumbs a text. We don't see to whom. He pockets it and walks.

CUT TO:

INT. SMALL CAFÉ — NIGHT

Warm light, half-empty. FEMME FATALE waits in a back booth — dressed for the club already, the armor of it: heels, lipstick, a coat she won't take off either. She's beautiful in the way that makes men assume she's in charge of something. She isn't, but she believes she is.

The PI slides in across from her. His knee won't stay still.

FEMME FATALE
You're doing the thing.

THE PI
What thing.

FEMME FATALE
The thing where you're already somewhere else.

THE PI
Long night ahead.

She studies him — reads more than he'd like, less than she thinks.

FEMME FATALE
I can't stay. I'm on at ten.
(beat)
Whatever it is — you don't have to.

THE PI
Yeah. I do.

She doesn't push. Pushing isn't a move she's been allowed to keep. She slides out, leans down, and kisses the top of his head — the one tender thing in the whole night.

FEMME FATALE
Text me when it's done.

She goes. The PI watches the door swing shut behind her. He sits a moment in the warm light like a man memorizing a room he won't see again.

Then he steps OUTSIDE —

EXT. CAFÉ — CONTINUOUS

— and sends one more text. This one we read, over his shoulder:

INSERT — PHONE SCREEN

     We still good for tonight?

BACK TO SCENE

He pockets the phone. Walks. We do NOT follow him back to the bar.

[[END OF PI BLOCK. The long take is over. The clock resets.]]

CUT TO:

INT. ABANDONED APARTMENT — NIGHT

[[HITMAN BLOCK BEGINS. New rhythm — fragmented, handheld, alive.]]

A room stripped to the studs. A chair. A shape in the chair we don't quite look at.

THE HITMAN — forties, unhurried, a craftsman at the end of a shift — rinses his hands in a dry sink that gives no water, wipes them on a rag instead. He lifts each shoe, checks the sole against the bare bulb. Clean. He turns the bulb off with a string.

On his right hand, catching the last of the light: a CLASS RING. Heavy. Old. The year stamped on it: '82.

He leaves.

CUT TO:

INT. SUV — MOVING — NIGHT

Music up loud. Two CREW MEMBERS — younger, wired — pass a folded bill and a hand mirror in the back. The Hitman drives, easy, one wrist on the wheel.

CREW #1
— so I'm saying, that's not a real tiger, that's a guy in the suit, the whole documentary's —

CREW #2
It's a real tiger.

CREW #1
It is NOT a real —

THE HITMAN
(mild, final)
It's a real tiger.

They laugh. They love this. The life, the night, the speed of it. The Hitman half-smiles and lets them have it.

CUT TO:

EXT. SMALL BUSINESS — STOREFRONT — NIGHT

The SUV at the curb. The Hitman stays behind the wheel, window cracked, a cigarette going. The two crew members go in.

INTERCUT — the calm of the car / the chaos inside: a register hitting the floor, a man pleading, glass. The Hitman taps ash out the window and watches the street, untouched by it, like weather happening to someone else.

The crew come out fast, grinning, getting in. The SUV pulls away smooth.

CUT TO:

INT. THE CLUB — NIGHT

[[LONG TRACKING SHOT — we follow the Hitman in.]]

Through the door, past the rope, through the heat and the bass and the bodies — the Hitman moves like he owns a small piece of every room he's ever been in. Nods. A hand on a shoulder. He's known here. He's liked here.

He reaches the back section. THE FEMALE MOB BOSS holds court on a low couch — older, sharp, the warmth of a woman who has decided to like you and the cold of one who could change her mind.

FEMALE MOB BOSS
There he is. My good one.

THE HITMAN
Boss.

She pats the seat. He sits. This is the longest, easiest exchange he's had all night — real fondness, the closest thing to family either of them has.

FEMALE MOB BOSS
You eat? You never eat.
(she presses an ENVELOPE into his hand)
Keep your phone on tonight. Something might move.

THE HITMAN
Always do.

FEMALE MOB BOSS
(holding his hand a second, the ring under her thumb)
Good boy.

Across the room, FEMME FATALE — working now, a tray on her hip — watches him from the far rail. She knows what he's walking toward. She set the table for it. She does not move. She does not warn him.

[[Her face: this is the closest she comes to agency, and it is the choice to do nothing.]]

The Hitman drifts to a quieter corner, checks his phone. The PI's text glows.

INSERT — PHONE SCREEN

     We still good for tonight?

He thumbs back:

     Yeah. Same time. Same place.

He pockets it. A goodbye here, a hand there. He heads for the door.

CUT TO:

EXT. NEIGHBORHOOD STREET — NIGHT

[[The stylized dolly returns — the SAME street, the SAME glide as the opening. The audience knows this block now.]]

The Hitman walks it the other direction. Toward the bar.

CUT TO:

INT. NEIGHBORHOOD BAR — NIGHT

[[CONVERGENCE. The timelines close.]]

The bar is exactly as we left it — one lamp, stools up, plastic sheeting breathing faintly in the back. Empty. No bartender. No witnesses.

The PI sits where the Bar Owner stood him up earlier. The Hitman comes in from the cold, easy, friendly, no idea.

THE HITMAN
You're early.

THE PI
Couldn't sleep.

THE HITMAN
(a small laugh)
Who can.
(thumbing toward the back)
Give me a second. Long night.

He goes.

INT. NEIGHBORHOOD BAR — RESTROOM — CONTINUOUS

The Hitman pushes each stall door — empty, empty. Runs the tap. Washes the night off his hands. Dries them. Draws the gun from his waistband, checks the load, the slide, the seat of the magazine. Ready. He tucks it back.

He looks at himself in the spotted mirror a moment. A tired man. Then he goes back out.

INT. NEIGHBORHOOD BAR — CONTINUOUS

The Hitman sits across from the PI. Two old professionals in an empty room.

And the PI is staring at his hand.

At the ring.

At '82.

The world narrows to it — the only thing left in the frame. The PI's partner's ring, on this man's finger, where it has no right to be.

The Hitman feels the look. Starts to follow it down to his own hand —

— and the PI MOVES.

Two knives — fast, ugly, nothing clean about it — PIN the Hitman's hands flat to the table. The Hitman ROARS. The PI is already up, already swinging the POOL CUE off the wall — not a fighter, a man possessed — wood cracking, the table skidding, the plastic sheeting shivering.

It is not choreography. It is grief with a weapon.

The PI stops, chest heaving. Reaches under the bar. A red can. He pours GASOLINE — over the table, the hands, the man — the smell of it filling the room.

He takes out a lighter.

The Hitman, pinned, gasping, finally finds the PI's eyes.

THE PI
(quiet)
You shouldn't have kept the ring.

He thumbs the lighter.

FADE OUT.

> END OF ACT I <
